Reason: The compound contains several functional groups that contribute to its melting point. A basic pyrazolopyrimidine structure as a starting point may have a melting point in the range of 200-250°C due to the planar, aromatic nature of the ring system and its ability to engage in strong intermolecular hydrogen bonding due to the multiple nitrogen atoms. Each methyl group can add roughly 5-10°C to the melting point due to the increased molecular weight and van der Waals forces. The azo group (N=N) has a minimal effect on melting point but may add 0-5°C due to the rigidity it introduces in the molecule. The additional phenyl ring may contribute an additional 5-10°C since it adds π-π interactions and van der Waals forces. Therefore, we estimate each methyl group (3 in total) adds 5°C, and the phenyl ring adds 10°C.

Starting with a base melting point around 200-220°C for a similar unsubstituted aromatic heterocycle seems reasonable. The presence of the five additional methyl groups may collectively add approximately 25-50°C, as each one increases the van der Waals interactions due to a larger molecular surface area, with an estimated 5-10°C per methyl group. The azo linkage generally increases rigidity that can facilitate better packing and thus, might add another 5-10°C. The additional phenyl ring is likely to add more than an alkyl side chain due to pi-pi interactions especially in a solid state, possibly accounting for a 15-20°C increase in melting point. Summing up these adjustments, we estimate a total increase of 45-80°C over the base structure's melting point.
